Section section_01 (Chars 0–8637):
Section Summary: In 1820, the remains of a great city in Middle Egypt were discovered, and in 1842-45, a Prussian expedition explored the site, now known as Tell el Amarna. In 1888, fellahin digging for marl stumbled upon clay tablets with writing, which were later secured by the government and found to be part of the Egyptian state archives from the time of Kings Amenophis III and IV. The tablets, written in Babylonian cuneiform, revealed that this language was used for diplomacy in the East around 1400 B.C. and included letters from Egyptian officials, Asiatic kings, and the Egyptian monarch. The discovery provided valuable insights into the administration and court of the Egyptian kings during the XVIIIth Dynasty, including the reigns of Amenophis III and IV, who introduced significant changes to the Egyptian religion and culture. The tablets also showcased the challenges of communication and writing in ancient times, with scribes using various techniques to overcome difficulties with the script and language.
